This event, which was closely followed by the Victory of the Revolution, resulted in political fragmentation of the state under two different, and often antagonistic, governments.

On the one hand, we have the National Transitional Council (NTC), which took over governing and replacing all state institutions after announcing the ending of the regime (on 20/10/2011). On the other hand, we have the General Congress, which practically dissolved the state institutions and which concluded to implement the power of the "temporary civic accord", leading to the establishment of another state – called the State of Libya Doctrine and Concept. Consequently, armed conflict broke out, although it quickly subsided without leading to the fall of the authority of the NTC.

On the ground in Gaddafi lands

The Libyan revolution started on 15 February 2011, and spread quickly throughout the country and even beyond its borders. A number of scholars have been labelled as having, or being on the verge of, actual blood on their hands because of their involvement in the revolt. Others are being watched to see whether they are truly supportive of the fight, or whether they are just bidding time until they can turn radical.
